      <bioghist id="aspace_18517a4b74e90a811a5b6193f4a4fda2">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Eugen Sandow (1867-1925), born Friedrich Wilhelm Müller, was a German strongman performer and bodybuilder who is credited with inventing the modern approach to bodybuilding. Sandow performed in circus and strongman competitions in Europe and the United States before opening a chain of public gymnasiums called the Institutes of Physical Culture, which offered classes on methods of exercise, dietary habits and weight training. He developed his own body to mimic the exact proportions of figures in Greek statues. In 1898, Sandow founded the monthly periodical <title>
               <part>Physical Culture</part>
            </title>, later renamed <title>
               <part>Sandow's Magazine of Physical Culture</part>
            </title>. He also authored a series of books, one of which coined the term "bodybuilding," designed exercise equipment, and organized international bodybuilding competitions.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_95f3c298a9a8c6ccdd5b38159be70db1">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Eugen Sandow bodybuilding lantern slides. Historical Library, Harvey Cushing / John Hay Whitney Medical Library, Yale University.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_44f11ab3eb09154a9b1aee2c6e48d1ff">
         <head>Content Description</head>
         <p>Includes 17 black and white lantern slides depicting Victorian bodybuilder Eugen Sandow in various poses, often mimicking Greek statues. Labels read "created by New York Camera Club," an amateur photography club formed in 1888 when a group split from the Society of Amateur Photographers. In 1897 the two clubs were joined back together as the Camera Club of New York.</p>
      </scopecontent>
